  "prompt": "What evolved into Homo sapiens?",
  "response": "Homo sapiens, or modern humans, evolved from earlier hominins in the genus Homo. The evolutionary lineage of Homo sapiens is believed to have included several species, with Homo erectus and Homo heidelbergensis being particularly significant predecessors.\n\nHomo erectus, which lived from approximately 1.9 million to 110,000 years ago, is one of the earliest members of the genus Homo and is thought to have been a direct ancestor of several later species, including Homo sapiens. Homo heidelbergensis, which lived around 600,000 to 200,000 years ago, is another important species in the evolutionary history of Homo sapiens. It is believed that Homo heidelbergensis gave rise to both Homo neanderthalensis (Neanderthals) and Homo sapiens.\n\nOver time, various evolutionary pressures and environmental changes led to the development of anatomical and behavioral characteristics that define modern humans. The exact pathways and timelines of this evolutionary process are still subjects of ongoing research and debate among scientists.",
